'''Virgil Roberts''' (April 13, 1922 &ndash; April 6, 2011)<ref>'A Life Remembered Former legislator Roberts dies,' '''La Crosse Tribune,''' Chris Hubbuch, April 8, 2011, B1</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[train dispatcher]], farmer and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] politician and legislator from [[Wisconsin]].
== Background == Born in [[Mindoro, Wisconsin]], Roberts was a [[train dispatcher]] and farmer. Later, Roberts served as a bank director. Roberts was rejected for military service during [[World War II]], because of a heart problem, but help the war effort by being a train dispatcher and worked for 37 years. He became interested in public service when he took a course at what is now [[Winona State University]].<ref>[http://dickinsonfuneralhome.com/obituaries/index.php?id=330 Obituary of Virgil Roberts, Dickinson Funeral Home]</ref> He served on the local school board.
== Legislative service == From 1971 until 1985 and then from 1987 until 1993, Roberts served in the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]] (he was an unsuccessful nominee for the [[Wisconsin State Senate]] in the 1984 election). He died in [[La Crosse, Wisconsin]].<ref>[http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp?action=view&term_id=2116&keyword=roberts Virgil Roberts, Wisconsin Historical Society]</ref>
